article.description: Swin Cash scored 15 points, all in the final nine minutes, and Deanna Nolan matched a career high with 18 points as the Detroit Shock defeated the visiting New York Liberty 88-83 Friday night.
article.headline: League leader Detroit wins fifth straight
article.linkText: Shock Cash-es in late to top Liberty
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- One year ago, the Detroit Shock finished with the WNBA's worst record at 9-23. It didn't take long for things to change. Detroit beat the New York Liberty 88-83 Friday night, giving the Shock the league's best record at 5-1. Their last four victories have come against teams that made the 2002 semifinals -- San Antonio, Washington, Los Angeles and New York. San Antonio made the playoffs last season as the Utah Starzz. "We talked a lot about how we were playing San Antonio, Washington, Los Angeles and New York right in a row, and what a crucial stretch that would be for us," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said. "To come out of it with four wins is a great achievement for a young ballclub." Swin Cash scored 15 points, all in the final nine minutes, and Deanna Nolan and Ruth Riley scored 18 apiece. That marked a new career high for Riley, and Nolan matched hers. "That's the makeup of this team -- it doesn't have to be the same person every night," Cash said. "The most impressive thing about this stretch isn't that we have won four but how we did it. We had to overcome things every night." New York (4-4) led by as many as 12 points in the second half but couldn't hold on. "I thought we played very well, but Detroit is just a terrific team," Liberty coach Richie Adubato said. "We had some key turnovers when we were up five late, and that turned the game around." With the score tied at 81, Nolan fouled Becky Hammon. She made both free throws, but Riley answered with a short jumper to tie it at 83. After a turnover by Hammon, Cash was fouled by Tamika Whitmore with 21 seconds left. She hit both shots, giving Detroit an 85-83 edge. Another turnover by Hammon forced New York to foul, and Elaine Powell hit one of two from the line to make it a three-point game. Crystal Robinson missed a tying 3-pointer, and Riley sealed the game from the line. "We knew Swin would come through -- she's a great player and she is also our leader," said Riley, who scored 14 points in the second half. "I just made an effort to be more aggressive, and I got some more shots." Robinson had a season-best 22 for New York, and Tamika Whitmore added 20. "Detroit is a much-improved team, but I think we lost that game ourselves," Robinson said. "We made crucial mistakes, and they came back and scored. We didn't play bad -- we just came up a little short." New York led 44-34 at the half, holding Cash scoreless in 15 minutes. Robinson had 17 in the half. Detroit trailed 65-54 midway through the second half but went on a 10-2 run to cut the margin to three. Riley had six of the 10 points. Cash scored 11 points in just over five minutes, including two free throws that put Detroit ahead 75-74 with 3:39 to play. It was the Shock's first lead since 8-7 early in the game. New York scored the next seven points, but Detroit came back with a 6-0 run, tying the score at 81-all on Powell's layup with 1:49 left. Game notes
Teresa Weatherspoon hit a second-half jumper to end a three-game scoreless streak. ... Cash didn't score her first points until 8:49 remained in the game. ... Kedra Holland-Corn had 14 points for the Shock, including 10 in the first half. ... This is the first time Detroit has been in first place this late in the season.
